[The above chronologically presented 6 samples were collected between
30 Apr and 30 May 2011 from 4 cattle and 2 sheep units. As apparent
from the dendogram appended to the report, the 5 samples No 2-6 (Ref
No: ISR/5/2011 to ISR/9/2011, collected between 9 - 30 May 2011)
belong to one cluster, while sample No 1 (Ref No: ISR/4/2011,
collected on 30 Apr 2011 from beef cattle in Yavneel) belongs to a
separate cluster, together with samples ISR/1/2011 and ISR/2/2011,
both collected 10-11 Mar 2011 from cattle in Bet-Zera. These samples
were addressed in WERLFMD Genotyping Report of 31 Mar 2011, batch
WRLFMD/2011/00016, discussed in (archived) 20110404.1044; the full
WRLFMD report is available at
http://www.wrlfmd.org/fmd_genotyping/2011/WRLFMD-2011-00016%20O%20Israel%202011.pdf.

These results may be interpreted as presenting 2 separate
introductions of the virus into Israel, one -- most probably -- from
Jordan, the other one from Lebanon, but a Syrian origin could not be
excluded (consult a political map).

Following the absence of FMD serotype O in Israel since Feb 2008, the
1st FMDV-O cluster was initially confirmed in Kibbutz Bet-Zera on 10
Mar 2011 in 10-months-old fattening calves. Date of start was,
reportedly, 1 Mar 2011. Bet-Zera is situated 3 km [1.6 miles] from the
Jordanian border. The other outbreak belonging to the same cluster, in
Yavneel, was suspected in grazing beef cattle on 21 Apr 2011.
Detection of FMD in animals on pasture is liable to delay, compared to
housed animals; the start of this outbreak may thus have taken place
earlier. Yavneel is 6.5 km [4 miles] distant from Bet Zera (Section 3
of the interactive map at
http://www.eyeonisrael.com/Israel-touring-map.html, south-west to
the Sea of Galilee; Bet Zera at x=388, y=515; Yavneel at x=316,
y=494).

The other cluster seems to have started in mid-April, initially
affecting fattening calves in Kibbutz Snir (Senir), 3 km from the
Lebanese border (more than 60 km [37.2 miles] north of
Bet-Zera/Yavneel). Similarly to Bet Zera, Senir is situated in an area
where abundant wild boar population is present on both sides of the
(double-fenced) border. The Senir farm had suffered FMD outbreaks
several times in the past, including December 2005 (ProMED-mail
archive no. 20051228.3691) and January 2008 (archive no. 20080203.0436). Remarkably, this highly invasive strain spread widely,
reaching Hadarom (south) district (sheep near Be'eri) and the West
Bank (see item 2). Both clusters demonstrate a high identity rate,
exceeding 98 percent, with the reference strain 'O/IRN/88/2009'; see
also the dendogram.

FMDV serotype O, topotype Middle-East South Asia (ME-SA),
genotype/strain: PanAsia, sub-lineage O/ME-SA/PanAsia-2 ANT-10, is
known to be circulating in vast areas of the Near East, from Iran in
the east to Bulgaria in the west. In order to try control the spread
of this virus strain, updated information from all regional countries
is urgently required. - Mod.AS]

